<h1>Portfolio Items<h1>



<%= link_to "Create New Item", new_portfolio_path %>

<p> <!-- the reason why rake routes only give new_portfolio
  and not new_portfolio_path is to give the user the ability
  to choose between path or url the difference
   between using _path or _url is that _path is relative
   path --> <p>
<% @portfolio_items.each do |portfolio_item| %>
  <p><%= link_to portfolio_item.title, portfolio_path(portfolio_item) %></p>
  <p> <!-- We are passing the portfolio_item.id portfolio_path(portfolio_item.id)
However rails knows that it will be the .id so we have removed it in an
effort to write less code

   --> <p>
  <p><%= portfolio_item.subtitle %></p>
  <p><%= portfolio_item.body %></p>
  <p><%= image_tag portfolio_item.thumb_image unless portfolio_item.thumb_image.nil? %></p>
<%= link_to "Edit Item", edit_portfolio_path(portfolio_item) %>
  <td><%= link_to 'Delete', portfolio_path(portfolio_item), method: :delete, data: { confirm: 'Are you sure?' } %></td
<br> <br>
<% end %>

<p> <!--
  The <% is a way to embed ruby script in an HTML file
  The @portfolio_items is fetching an array
  the .each is causing it to loop through the whole array
  the portfolio_item is the variable it puts it in with each loop
  it then displays the portfolio_item.title .subtitle
  .body etc all the ones we have listed under <%=


  To display the data from a ruby variable you need
  to place the <%= note the equal -->
  </p>
